# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] On July 23, 1984, an explosion and fire took place at a Union Oil Lemont Refinery in Romeoville, Illinois, outside Chicago, killing 17 people and causing major property damage.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The explosive force propelled the upper portion 14 metres (46 ft) of the vessel a distance of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) from its original location, while the base remained at the center of the resultant fire.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The tower was constructed from 25 millimetres (0.98 in) thick plates of type ASTM A516 Grade 70 steel per ASME Section VIII pressure vessel code.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The vessel was 18.8 metres (62 ft) tall, 2.6 metres (8.5 ft) in diameter.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] Beginning in 1970 the vessel served as an amine absorber tower, used to strip hydrogen sulfide from a process stream of propane and butane.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] In 1974, plant inspection identified hydrogen blisters and laminations in the shell of the vessel, and the refinery replaced several meters of the lower shell section using manual metal arc welding.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] After welding, no post weld heat treatment (PWHT) was performed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] PWHT is a vital process that reduces residual stresses formed during welding, and restores the macro structure of the steel.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] In 1976, a Monel liner was installed on the bottom head to reduce corrosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The shell section replaced in 1974 was not covered by this new liner.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] Shortly before 6 pm that day, a worker making a routine hourly check of the tower discovered a hairline crack in a horizontal circular weld.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The operator attempted to close the main inlet valve to the tower to stop gas leaking from the 150 millimetres (5.9 in) crack.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The crack grew to 600 millimetres (24 in) and the operator initiated an evacuation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The crack continued to grow and a significant quantity of flammable gas was released as company fire fighters gathered at the scene.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The gas ignited, killing 17, seriously injuring 10 others, damaging the refinery, and launching the upper portion of the vessel to 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) from its original location.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] Failure analysis of the vessel segments included the following non-destructive testing methods.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The cause of cracking did not become clear until metallographic results were combined with stress corrosion cracking and hydrogen embrittlement tests, followed by fracture mechanics analysis.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] It appeared that an already existing crack had extended through more than 90% of the wall thickness and was about 800 mm in length.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] Further, it was determined that hydrogen embrittlement had reduced the fracture resistance of the steel by more than half.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The vessel had been put into service in 1970 and had undergone several repairs and modifications before the July 1984 incident.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The vessel was fractured along a path that was weakened by extensive cracking adjacent to a repair weld joining a replacement section to the original vessel.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] These pre-existing cracks initiated in areas of hard microstructure known to be susceptible to hydrogen stress cracking.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] This hard microstructure formed during the repair welding of the replacement section.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] The cracks grew through the vessel wall as a result of hydrogen pressure cracking.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] When the depth of the largest of these pre-existing cracks exceeded 90% to 95% of the wall thickness, the remaining thin ligament of steel in the cracked section ruptured and leakage occurred.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/1984-romeoville-petroleum-refinery-disaster] This crack caused a complete fracture of the vessel circumference at the operating stress level of only 35 MPa (roughly 10% of the rated strength of the steel) because the toughness of the vessel steel had been reduced by hydrogen embrittlement.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] On 6 August 2018, the collision of a liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) road tanker with an articulated lorry carrying flammable solvents and a car transporter resulted in a huge explosion on the A14 motorway within Borgo Panigale, a neighbourhood of Bologna, Italy.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] It was a case of boiling-liquid expanding-vapour explosion (BLEVE), where nearly all the road tanker cargo combusted in a matter of seconds upon release, generating a tremendous amount of thermal radiation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The accident killed two people, injured 145 and caused significant damage to the surrounding commercial and residential area.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] One span of the viaduct where it happened collapsed and a gash opened in the motorway.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The collision involved a liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) road tanker, another articulated lorry carrying flammable solvents, and a car transporter.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] It took place on the northbound carriageway of the *ramo Casalecchio* (Casalecchio branch) of the A14 motorway, which connects the A1 motorway to the A14 main route, within Borgo Panigale, a neighbourhood of Bologna, Italy.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The stretch of motorway where the collision occurred crosses a densely populated area in the outskirts of Bologna and is flanked on both sides by the Tangenziale di Bologna, or Bologna ring road.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Luckily, many businesses were closed due to the summer holidays.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The collision was caused by the road tanker, which rear-ended a near-stationary lorry laden with class-3 flammable solvents in intermediate bulk containers (IBC).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Pushed from behind by the impact, the second lorry rear-ended the car transporter directly in front.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Cameras captured the tanker heading straight into the preceding vehicle, which possibly eliminates the hypothesis of mechanical failure, because steering and brakes would have needed to fail at the same time.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The driver was complying with all applicable rest regulations and speed limit.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The tanker pressure vessel was also mechanically sound.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The amount of LPG in the tanker was estimated at 23 or 25 tonnes.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The cargo of the rear-ended lorry ignited immediately, which resulted in a large pool fire engulfing the affected vehicles.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The source of ignition was either engine or exhaust hot surfaces or mechanical sparks.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] By chance, police units were on the spot at the time of the collision and diverted traffic away, both on the motorway and the adjacent urban roads.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The pressure vessel of the LPG tanker did not breach as a direct consequence of the crash.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] However, it was surrounded by flames from the pool fire.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The vessel was not fire-proofed nor did it have a relief valve.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Neither arrangement is required by Italian regulations or in the international ADR agreement.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Seven minutes and 20 seconds after the collision, the tank failed due to loss of mechanical properties caused by external heating.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Fire services did not have sufficient time to reach the location before the explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The fireball diameter was estimated at more than 170 metres (560 ft) and its height above ground at 130 metres (430 ft).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] This BLEVE is notable because it caused the collapse of the span of viaduct on which it happened.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Computer simulations have assessed a blast overpressure of about 500 kPa at short distances from the source, a value sufficient to cause the failure of a road bridge like the one involved in the explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Given the tremendous thermal radiation, people within a radius of 100 metres (330 ft) from the exploded road tanker would have died or received major injuries.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The explosion sent fragments hundreds of meters away and shattered windows up to 500 metres (1,600 ft) away.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Buildings were damaged as far as 200 metres (660 ft) away.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] A nearby car dealer lot caught fire and all the cars on sale were destroyed as a consequence.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] A second car dealer on-sale stock was also affected.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Fires were extinguished two hours after the explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The road tanker driver died on the spot upon the first collision.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Thirteen among those hospitalized were policemen (11 carabinieri and two from the Polizia Stradale, or the Italian highway patrol).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] Prime minister Giuseppe Conte visited the injured at the Ospedale Maggiore in Bologna, where most of the wounded had been hospitalized, and the burn unit in Cesena.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2018-borgo-panigale-explosion] The other burn victims had been transported to the Parma burn unit.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] In the early morning of June 21, 2019, a fire and multiple explosions occurred at the Philadelphia Energy Solutions (PES) refinery in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] A release of hydrocarbons and hydrofluoric acid in the refinery's alkylation unit caused a ground-hugging vapor cloud which rapidly ignited, leading to three separate explosions minutes apart from each other.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The largest explosion, a BLEVE, sent a vessel fragment flying 2,000 feet (610 m) across the Schuylkill River.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Five employees sustained minor injuries, but there were ultimately no fatalities.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The refinery announced it would shut down operations the same month, and filed for bankruptcy a month later.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The Philadelphia Energy Solutions refinery was an oil refinery complex in Philadelphia.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] It was first used in 1866 by the Atlantic Petroleum Storage Company, who built the complex to store and transport petroleum and its byproducts.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] By 1870, the company had become Philadelphia's largest employer and a leader in exporting lighting fuel.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] To meet growing demands, the Gulf Oil Company built a second refinery at Girard Point by the 1920s.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The neighborhood surrounding the refinery sites, largely farms and marshlands, began to develop housing and transportation infrastructure as the refineries expanded.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The construction of the Schuylkill Expressway and Platt Bridge transformed the area into a major transportation crossroads.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Public housing was built by the Philadelphia Housing Authority and federal government, including directly across from the highway.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The current refinery site resulted from the integration of the Girard Point and Point Breeze refineries under Sunoco.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Unable to afford changes that would allow the refinery to process cheaper crude oils, the refinery relied on expensive imported oils that put it at a comparative disadvantage.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] After Sunoco announced their intent to close or sell the complex, Philadelphia Energy Solutions was founded by Phil Rinaldi to buy and maintain operations.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] On the morning of June 21, 2019, the refinery's alkylation unit, which produced high-quality gasoline, was functioning normally.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] However, shortly after 4:00 am, a leak of liquefied hydrocarbon gas (mostly propane) containing about 2.5% hydrofluoric acid (HF) developed from a ruptured pipe elbow at the discharge of a pump.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] At the time, three field operators were working in the alkylation unit.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] At 4:01 am, one of the operators reported seeing a ground-hugging vapor cloud, estimated by another to be 10 feet (3.0 m) high.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] At 4:02 am, the vapor cloud ignited in the unit, causing a massive fire.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The field operators in the alkylation unit were able to flee the area and avoid injury.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] At 4:03 am, a remote control room operator activated the refinery's rapid acid deinventory (RAD) system, routing approximately 339,000 pounds (154,000 kg) of hydrofluoric acid into an isolated drum for sequestration and safety.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] At 4:12 am, the control room operator attempted to activate the water cannons which were designed to reduce airborne HF through vapor suppression, but the system failed to respond.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] In fact, the associated control system had failed at 4:02 am, and its backup uninterruptible power supply failed 9 seconds afterwards.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] One field operator attempted to walk to the water pumps to manually activate them but reported they were too hot at the time to approach.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] At 4:15 am, the first explosion occurred in the alkylation unit, followed by a second explosion at 4:19 am.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Then, at 4:22 am, a vessel containing flammable hydrocarbons (primarily butylene, isobutane, and *n*-butane) ruptured and caused the largest blast, a boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion (BLEVE).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Fragments of the vessel, one weighing approximately 38,000 pounds (17,000 kg) and two other fragments weighing approximately 15,500 pounds (7,000 kg) and 23,000 pounds (10,000 kg), were sent flying; the largest fragment was propelled 2,000 feet (610 m) across the Schuylkill River.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] At 4:39 am, the alkylation unit shift supervisor entered the alkylation unit in firefighting protective bunker gear and manually activated the water pumps to help suppress the release of hydrofluoric acid from the alkylation unit.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Residents who lived east of the plant were ordered to shelter in place.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The fire burned for over 24 hours before it was extinguished at approximately 8:30 am on June 22, 2019, and the shelter-in-place order was lifted.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Chemical Safety Board released its final report on the incident on October 11, 2022.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The report stated that a corroded elbow pipe, installed in 1973, ruptured and caused the initial leak.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] PES announced it would halt operations completely on June 26, 2019, and filed for bankruptcy on July 22.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The shutdown reduced US refining capacity by about 2%.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] As of 2022, developers were looking into redeveloping the site of the refinery.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] On October 8, 2024, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) announced it had reached a settlement of $4.2 million with Philadelphia Energy Solutions.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] In the settlement, the EPA found that the company had failed to identify and assess the risk posed by a pipe elbow in the hydrofluoric acid alkylation unit.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Last installed in 1973, the pipe ruptured due to "extensive" corrosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] The EPA states that the lawsuit marked the largest amount sought under the Clean Air Act Rule, which requires owners to ensure that hazardous substances are safely managed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] However, the company did not admit to liability in the settlement plan.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Bankruptcy Court in Delaware following the company's declaration of bankruptcy after the explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/2019-philadelphia-refinery-explosion] Philadelphia Energy Solutions remains under a clean-up agreement in collaboration with the EPA and Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] It was not until the fifteenth century that Alcanar was incorporated as an independent town, but it had been populated for a long time before then.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] From 1148 the town was part of the municipality of Ulldecona.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] After it was granted independence, it received the name of the Canar, which originates from *republic of its inhabitants*.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The original charter was granted in February 1239, however the settlement did not stabilise until it was granted a new charter in 1252, the date regarded as the real foundation of the town.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] In 1380, the village already contained thirty families, and they were subjected to various attacks by Saracen pirates, which led to the construction of a lookout tower in the fourteenth century.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] As a precaution, the town was fortified and walled.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] In 1449, the town became independent of Ulldecona.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] During the war against John II of Castile, the town was occupied by troops of the king, who burned the town.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] During the reign of Philip II, various defense towers were built to repel attacks by Turkish pirates, and Alcanar was again fortified.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] In the Catalan Revolt of 1640–59, the town remained loyal to the king of Castile, which led to occupation of the city by Catalan troops.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] A similar event occurred during the Peninsular War.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Later, during the First Carlist War, the city was besieged.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] It was captured and looted by Carlist troops who held a strong position in the town for a time.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] On July 11, 1978, a tanker truck carrying flammable liquid exploded in front of the Camping de los Alfaques located at the coast, outside the town, killing 217 people, injuring more than 300 and completely devastating the campsite.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] On August 16, 2017, an explosion in a house outside of the town, at the coast, killed two people and injured another.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The next day, August 17, there was a second explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Later it was learned that those killed and wounded were terrorists and the explosion was caused by bombs built by the jihadist cell responsible for the 2017 Barcelona attacks.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The Alcanar parish church dedicated to Saint Michael (*Sant Miquel* in Catalan or *San Miguel* in Spanish) is a major feature of the municipality.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The church is built in the Renaissance style, with a single nave and side chapels; it originally consisted of four bays with a semicircular apse, which disappeared in some nineteenth century rebuilding.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] It was then expanded with a transept, dome base and a sanctuary.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] It currently measures 19 metres wide and has a total height of 16 metres.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The access door is a half-point arch framed by two columns, and at the top are three niches framed by a triangular pediment.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The belltower has a square base and windows on each side.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] On the outskirts of the village is a shrine devoted to the Mare de Déu del Remei (Our Lady of Good Remedy).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] It was built in the late sixteenth century and early seventeenth in a Gothic style.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] In the eighteenth century, a belltower, a crossing and a dome were added and the interior was expanded.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Next to the shrine is the building of the former guest house in which retains a mosaic that represents the battle of Lepanto.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The mosaic was part of the floor of the chapel until it was removed in the early nineteenth century, and as a result is very deteriorated.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The image is venerated at the shrine is a small class of about 60 centimetres of the eighteenth century.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The temple interior is decorated with a series of paintings made in 1920.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The former altar pieces and part of the decoration were destroyed in 1936.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Along the coast are the defence towers, which were built between 1530 and 1630 to fend off pirates.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] They are all square, with door with voussoir, floor and vault.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Most of them have been renovated, and are now used as houses or summer residences.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Tourism and second homes are a prominent factor in the Alcan economy.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Near the Alcanar Beach, many housing developments have been built that increase the number of tourists during the summer months.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] One of the oldest summer residences is known as Clos de Codorniu, and once was home to King Alfonso XIII of Spain.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] It also has several hotels and campsites and other facilities designed to cater to tourism.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Most tourists stay at the old and relatively quiet fishing village of Les Cases d'Alcanar or in Alcanar-Platja during the summer season.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The small settlement of La Selleta was built by Germans on a hill below the Serra del Montsià in the last half of the 20th century.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Agricultural activity continues to develop in the northern town, the furthest from the coast, mainly growing crops of oranges and clementines.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] Fishing remains important in Alcanar's smaller villages, and they are especially dedicated to catching prawns.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcanar] The Port of Alcanar is a facility serving the cement plant on the southside of the town.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In chemistry, an **alcohol** (from Arabic *al-kuḥl* 'the kohl') is a type of organic compound that carries at least one hydroxyl (−OH) functional group bound to a saturated carbon atom.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols range from the simple, like methanol and ethanol, to complex, like sugar alcohols and cholesterol.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The presence of an OH group strongly modifies the properties of hydrocarbons, conferring hydrophilic (water-attracted) properties.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The OH group provides a site at which many reactions can occur.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The flammable nature of the exhalations of wine was already known to ancient natural philosophers such as Aristotle (384–322 BCE), Theophrastus (c.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] However, this did not immediately lead to the isolation of alcohol, even despite the development of more advanced distillation techniques in second- and third-century Roman Egypt.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] An important recognition, first found in one of the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (ninth century CE), was that by adding salt to boiling wine, which increases the wine's relative volatility, the flammability of the resulting vapors may be enhanced.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In the twelfth century, recipes for the production of *aqua ardens* ("burning water", i.e., alcohol) by distilling wine with salt started to appear in a number of Latin works, and by the end of the thirteenth century, it had become a widely known substance among Western European chemists.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still, by which an alcohol purity of 90% could be obtained.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The medicinal properties of ethanol were studied by Arnald of Villanova (1240–1311 CE) and John of Rupescissa (c.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] 1310–1366), the latter of whom regarded it as a life-preserving substance able to prevent all diseases (the *aqua vitae* or "water of life", also called by John the *quintessence* of wine).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The word "alcohol" derives from the Arabic *kohl* (Arabic: الكحل, romanized: *al-kuḥl*), a powder used as an eyeliner.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The first part of the word (*al-*) is the Arabic definite article, equivalent to *the* in English.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The second part of the word (*kuḥl*) has several antecedents in Semitic languages, ultimately deriving from the Akkadian 𒎎𒋆𒁉𒍣𒁕 (*guḫlum*), meaning stibnite or antimony.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Like its antecedents in Arabic and older languages, the term *alcohol* was originally used for the very fine powder produced by the sublimation of the natural mineral stibnite to form antimony trisulfide Sb2S3.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] It was considered to be the essence or "spirit" of this mineral.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] It was used as an antiseptic, eyeliner, and cosmetic.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Later the meaning of alcohol was extended to distilled substances in general, and then narrowed again to ethanol, when "spirits" was a synonym for hard liquor.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Paracelsus and Libavius both used the term *alcohol* to denote a fine powder, the latter speaking of an *alcohol* derived from antimony.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] At the same time Paracelsus uses the word for a volatile liquid; *alcool* or *alcool vini* occurs often in his writings.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The 1657 *Lexicon Chymicum* by William Johnson glosses the word as "antimonium sive stibium." By extension, the word came to refer to any fluid obtained by distillation, including "alcohol of wine," the distilled essence of wine.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Libavius in *Alchymia* (1594) refers to "vini alcohol vel vinum alcalisatum".
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The term *ethanol* was invented in 1892, blending "ethane" with the "-ol" ending of "alcohol", which was generalized as a libfix.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The term *alcohol* originally referred to the primary alcohol ethanol (ethyl alcohol), which is used as a drug and is the main alcohol present in alcoholic drinks.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* appears in the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) chemical name of all substances where the hydroxyl group is the functional group with the highest priority.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] When a higher priority group is present in the compound, the prefix *hydroxy-* is used in its IUPAC name.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* in non-IUPAC names (such as paracetamol or cholesterol) also typically indicates that the substance is an alcohol.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] However, some compounds that contain hydroxyl functional groups have *trivial names* that do not include the suffix *-ol* or the prefix *hydroxy-*, e.g. the sugars glucose and sucrose.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] IUPAC nomenclature is used in scientific publications, and in writings where precise identification of the substance is important.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In naming simple alcohols, the name of the alkane chain loses the terminal *e* and adds the suffix *-ol*, *e.g.*, as in "ethanol" from the alkane chain name "ethane".
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] When necessary, the position of the hydroxyl group is indicated by a number between the alkane name and the *-ol*: propan-1-ol for CH3CH2CH2OH, propan-2-ol for CH3CH(OH)CH3.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] If a higher priority group is present (such as an aldehyde, ketone, or carboxylic acid), then the prefix *hydroxy-*is used, e.g., as in 1-hydroxy-2-propanone (CH3C(O)CH2OH).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Compounds having more than one hydroxy group are called polyols.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] They are named using suffixes -diol, -triol, etc., following a list of the position numbers of the hydroxyl groups, as in propane-1,2-diol for CH3CH(OH)CH2OH (propylene glycol).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In cases where the hydroxy group is bonded to an sp2 carbon on an aromatic ring, the molecule is classified separately as a phenol and is named using the IUPAC rules for naming phenols.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Phenols have distinct properties and are not classified as alcohols.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In other less formal contexts, an alcohol is often called with the name of the corresponding alkyl group followed by the word "alcohol", e.g., methyl alcohol, ethyl alcohol.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Propyl alcohol may be *n*-propyl alcohol or isopropyl alcohol, depending on whether the hydroxyl group is bonded to the end or middle carbon on the straight propane chain.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] As described under systematic naming, if another group on the molecule takes priority, the alcohol moiety is often indicated using the "hydroxy-" prefix.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In archaic nomenclature, alcohols can be named as derivatives of methanol using "-carbinol" as the ending.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] For instance, (CH3)3COH can be named trimethylcarbinol.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols are then classified into primary, secondary (*sec-*, *s-*), and tertiary (*tert-*, *t-*), based upon the number of carbon atoms connected to the carbon atom that bears the hydroxyl functional group.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The respective numeric shorthands 1°, 2°, and 3° are sometimes used in informal settings.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The primary alcohols have general formulas RCH2OH.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest primary alcohol is methanol (CH3OH), for which R = H, and the next is ethanol, for which R = CH3, the methyl group.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary alcohols are those of the form RR'CHOH, the simplest of which is 2-propanol (R = R' = CH3).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] For the tertiary alcohols, the general form is RR'R"COH.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest example is *tert*-butanol (2-methylpropan-2-ol), for which each of R, R', and R" is CH3.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In these shorthands, R, R', and R" represent substituents, alkyl or other attached, generally organic groups.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols have a long history of myriad uses.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol is the most common industrial alcohol, with about 12 million tons/y produced in 1980.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The combined capacity of the other alcohols is about the same, distributed roughly equally.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] With respect to acute toxicity, simple alcohols have low acute toxicities.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Doses of several milliliters are tolerated.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] For pentanols, hexanols, octanols, and longer alcohols, LD50 range from 2–5 g/kg (rats, oral).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol and ethylene glycol are more toxic than other simple alcohols.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Their metabolism is affected by the presence of ethanol, which has a higher affinity for liver alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In this way, methanol will be excreted intact in urine.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In general, the hydroxyl group makes alcohols polar.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Those groups can form hydrogen bonds to one another and to most other compounds.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Owing to the presence of the polar OH alcohols are more water-soluble than simple hydrocarbons.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol, ethanol, and propanol are miscible in water.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] 1-Butanol, with a four-carbon chain, is moderately soluble.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Because of hydrogen bonding, alcohols tend to have higher boiling points than comparable hydrocarbons and ethers.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The boiling point of the alcohol ethanol is 78.29 °C, compared to 69 °C for the hydrocarbon hexane, and 34.6 °C for diethyl ether.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols occur widely in nature, as derivatives of glucose such as cellulose and hemicellulose, and in phenols and their derivatives such as lignin.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Starting from biomass, 180 billion tons/y of complex carbohydrates (sugar polymers) are produced commercially (as of 2014).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Many other alcohols are pervasive in organisms, as manifested in other sugars such as fructose and sucrose, in polyols such as glycerol, and in some amino acids such as serine.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Simple alcohols like methanol, ethanol, and propanol occur in modest quantities in nature, and are industrially synthesized in large quantities for use as chemical precursors, fuels, and solvents.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Many alcohols are produced by hydroxylation, i.e., the installation of a hydroxy group using oxygen or a related oxidant.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Hydroxylation is the means by which the body processes many poisons, converting lipophilic compounds into hydrophilic derivatives that are more readily excreted.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Enzymes called hydroxylases and oxidases facilitate these conversions.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Many industrial alcohols, such as cyclohexanol for the production of nylon, are produced by hydroxylation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In the Ziegler process, linear alcohols are produced from ethylene and triethylaluminium followed by oxidation and hydrolysis.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The process generates a range of alcohols that are separated by distillation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Many higher alcohols are produced by hydroformylation of alkenes followed by hydrogenation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Such processes give fatty alcohols, which are useful for detergents.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Industry produces low-weight molecular alcohols (e.g. ethanol, isopropanol, 2-butanol, and *tert*-butanol) through the acid-catalyzed hydration of alkenes, the latter typically from cracking fractions of distilled crude oil.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Two implementations are employed: the direct and indirect methods.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In the indirect method, the alkene is converted to a sulfate ester, which is subsequently hydrolyzed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The direct method eschews intermediates, instead using water to quench an intermediate carbocation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Less aggressive reagents suffice for vicinal difunctionalization.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In industry, the diol ethylene glycol forms when ethylene oxide is hydrolyzed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In the laboratory, sulfuric acid also catalyzes hydration of alkenes to secondary or tertiary alcohols.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] More controllable net hydrations proceed in multiple steps, with a vicinally-functionalized intermediate.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Thus oxymercuration initially forms an organomercury alcohol, which can then undergo reductive demetalation; and alkenes react with *N*-bromosuccinimide and water to form halohydrins.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In hydroboration-oxidation and the related Mukaiyama hydration, an alkene is hydrometalated, then oxidized.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Ethanol is obtained by fermentation of glucose (which is often obtained from starch) in the presence of yeast.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Like ethanol, butanol can be produced by fermentation processes.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] *Saccharomyces* yeast are known to produce these higher alcohols at temperatures above 75 °F (24 °C).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The bacterium *Clostridium acetobutylicum* can feed on cellulose (also an alcohol) to produce butanol on an industrial scale.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alkyl halides react with aqueous NaOH or KOH to give alcohols in nucleophilic aliphatic substitution.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary and especially tertiary alkyl halides will give the elimination (alkene) product instead.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Grignard reagents react with carbonyl groups to give secondary and tertiary alcohols.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Related reactions are the Barbier reaction and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Aldehydes or ketones are reduced with sodium borohydride or lithium aluminium hydride (after an acidic workup).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Another reduction using aluminium isopropoxide is the Meerwein–Ponndorf–Verley reduction.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Noyori asymmetric hydrogenation is the asymmetric reduction of β-keto-esters.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] With aqueous p*K*a values of around 16–19, alcohols are, in general, slightly weaker acids than water.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] With strong bases such as sodium hydride or sodium they form salts called *alkoxides*, with the general formula RO−M+ (where R is an alkyl and M is a metal).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The acidity of alcohols is strongly affected by solvation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In the gas phase, alcohols are more acidic than in water.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In DMSO, alcohols (and water) have a p*K*a of around 29–32.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] As a consequence, alkoxides (and hydroxide) are powerful bases and nucleophiles (e.g., for the Williamson ether synthesis) in this solvent.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In particular, RO− or HO− in DMSO can be used to generate significant equilibrium concentrations of acetylide ions through the deprotonation of alkynes (see Favorskii reaction).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with hydrochloric acid to produce tertiary alkyl chloride.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Primary and secondary alcohols are converted to the corresponding chlorides using thionyl chloride and various phosphorus chloride reagents.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] In the Barton–McCombie deoxygenation an alcohol is deoxygenated to an alkane with tributyltin hydride or a trimethylborane-water complex in a radical substitution reaction.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Meanwhile, the oxygen atom has lone pairs of nonbonded electrons that render it weakly basic in the presence of strong acids such as sulfuric acid.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Upon treatment with strong acids, alcohols undergo the E1 elimination reaction to produce alkenes.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction, in general, obeys Zaytsev's rule, which states that the most stable (usually the most substituted) alkene is formed.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols are eliminated easily at just above room temperature, but primary alcohols require a higher temperature.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] A more controlled elimination reaction requires the formation of the xanthate ester.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with strong acids to generate carbocations.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction is related to their dehydration, e.g. isobutylene from *tert*-butyl alcohol.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] A special kind of dehydration reaction involves triphenylmethanol and especially its amine-substituted derivatives.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] When treated with acid, these alcohols lose water to give stable carbocations, which are commercial dyes.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohol and carboxylic acids react in the so-called Fischer esterification.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Other types of ester are prepared in a similar manner−for example, tosyl (tosylate) esters are made by reaction of the alcohol with 4-toluenesulfonyl chloride in pyridine.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alcohols (R−CH2OH) can be oxidized either to aldehydes (R−CHO) or to carboxylic acids (R−CO2H).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The oxidation of secondary alcohols (R1R2CH−OH) normally terminates at the ketone (R1R2C=O) stage.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols (R1R2R3C−OH) are resistant to oxidation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids normally proceeds via the corresponding aldehyde, which is transformed via an *aldehyde hydrate* (R−CH(OH)2) by reaction with water before it can be further oxidized to the carboxylic acid.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] Reagents useful for the transformation of primary alcohols to aldehydes are normally also suitable for the oxidation of secondary alcohols to ketones.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] These include Collins reagent and Dess–Martin periodinane.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids can be carried out using potassium permanganate or the Jones reagent.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The **American Institute of Chemical Engineers** (**AIChE**) is a professional organization for chemical engineers.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE was established in 1908 to distinguish chemical engineers as professionals independent of chemists and mechanical engineers.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] By 2024, AIChE had over 60,000 members from over 110 countries (sources vary).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] There are over 350 active student chapters at universities worldwide.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Student chapters aim to provide networking opportunities in academia and industry as well as increase student involvement locally and nationally.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] This section consists of excerpts from a historical pamphlet written for the Silver Anniversary of the AICHE in 1932.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] In 1905, *The Chemical Engineer* rounded out its first year of publication with an editorial by its founder and prominent engineer, Richard K.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meade, that propounded the question: "Why not the American Society of Chemical Engineers?" He went on to say: "The profession is now a recognized one and there are probably at least five hundred chemical engineers in this country".
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mechanical, civil, electrical, and mining engineers in the United States each had already established a national society, so Meade's editorial was quite pertinent.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] But it took time for the idea to take root and Meade kept promoting it for the next two years.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Finally, in 1907, he issued a call for a preliminary meeting to be held in Atlantic City in June 1907.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Some early leaders of the profession, Charles F.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler, and Thorn Smith along with about a dozen others answered Meade's call and met in Atlantic City on June 21, 1907.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The meeting concluded with the formation of an organizing committee of six members: Charles F.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee sent a letter in September 1908 to 600 men in the chemical profession in the United States and Canada asking for their opinions about forming a chemical engineering society.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Two hundred replies were received and 70-80% were favorable.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Many of the others believed the existing societies (especially the American Chemical Society) were sufficient and they did not favor forming a new society.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The organizing committee decided to hold a larger, open meeting at the Hotel Belmont in New York City at which those opposed to forming the new society could present their arguments and opinions.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Accordingly, they invited fifty men prominent in the chemical profession (including men who opposed the forming of a new society) to meet on January 18, 1908.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Twenty-one men attended the meeting and fourteen others expressed their views in letters.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] After much discussion, the meeting ended without reaching a definitive decision.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] However, it was agreed to have a mail vote (on whether or not to form a chemical engineering society) after a complete stenographic report of the meeting was printed and sent to the fifty men who had been invited to the meeting.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The mail vote resulted in 36 replies of which 22 were in the affirmative, 6 were negative, and 8 were neutral.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Based on those voting results, the organizing committee of six called for a full-fledged organizational meeting to be held in Philadelphia on June 22, 1908.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Meanwhile, the committee of six drafted a proposed constitution to be presented at that meeting.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] That meeting resulted in the official formation of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers, the adoption of a constitution, and the election of Samuel P.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Sadtler as the first president of the Institute.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] Divisions and forums provide technical information, programming for AIChE's technical meetings, and awards and recognition to outstanding chemical engineers in their areas of expertise.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] They also provide opportunities for affiliation with top engineers in the general disciplines as well as in emerging fields like biotechnology and sustainability.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] The prerequisite qualifications for election to any of the membership grades are available in the AIChE Bylaws.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] As new technology is developed, there is a need for experts to collaborate to achieve common goals.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/american-institute-of-chemical-engineers] AIChE plays a major role through joint initiatives with industry, academia, and others.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A **boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion** (**BLEVE**; /ˈblɛvi/ *BLEV-ee*) is an explosion caused by the rupture of a vessel containing a pressurized liquid that has attained a temperature sufficiently higher than its boiling point at atmospheric pressure.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Because the boiling point of a liquid rises with pressure, the contents of the pressurized vessel can remain a liquid as long as the vessel is intact.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the vessel's integrity is compromised, the loss of pressure drops the boiling point, which can cause a portion of the liquid to boil and form a cloud of rapidly expanding vapor.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] BLEVEs are manifestations of explosive boiling.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the vapor is flammable (as is the case with compounds such as hydrocarbons and alcohols) and comes in contact with an ignition source, further damage can be caused by the ensuing explosion and fireball.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, BLEVEs do not necessarily involve fire.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] On 24 April 1957, a process reactor at a Factory Mutual (FM) facility underwent a powerful explosion as a consequence of a rapid depressurization.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] It contained formalin mixed with phenol.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, no fire developed, as the mixture was not flammable.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In the wake of the accident, researchers James B.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Walls, who were employed with FM, came up with the terms "boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion" and its acronym "BLEVE".
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The expressions did not become of common use until the early 1970s, when the National Fire Protection Association's (NFPA) *Fire Command* and *Fire Journal* magazines started publishing articles using them.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A containment vessel maintaining the pressure that keeps the substance in liquid form.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A sudden loss of containment that rapidly drops the pressure.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Typically, a BLEVE starts with a vessel containing liquid held above its atmospheric-pressure boiling temperature.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Many substances normally stored as liquids, such as carbon dioxide, propane, and other industrial gases have boiling temperatures below room temperature when at atmospheric pressure.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In the case of water, a BLEVE could occur if a pressure vessel is heated beyond 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] That container, because the boiling water pressurizes it, must be capable of holding liquid water at very high temperatures.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the pressurized vessel ruptures, the pressure which prevents the liquid from boiling is lost.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the rupture is catastrophic, i.e., the vessel becomes suddenly no longer capable of holding any pressure, then the liquid will find itself at a temperature far above its boiling point.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] This causes a portion of the liquid to instantaneously vaporize with extremely rapid expansion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Depending on temperatures, pressures, and the material involved, the expansion may be so rapid that it can be classified as an explosion, fully capable of inflicting severe damage on its surroundings.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For example, a tank of pressurized liquid water held at 350 °C (662 °F) might be pressurized to 10 MPa (1,500 psi) above atmospheric (or gauge) pressure.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] At atmospheric pressure the boiling point of water is 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Liquid water at atmospheric pressure does not exist at temperatures higher than 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] At that moment, the water would boil and turn to vapor explosively, and the 350 °C (662 °F) liquid water turned to gas would take up significantly more volume (≈ 1,600-fold) than it did as liquid, causing a vapor explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Such explosions can happen when the superheated water of a boiler escapes through a crack in a boiler, causing a boiler explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The vaporization of liquid resulting in a BLEVE typically occurs within 1 millisecond after a catastrophic loss of containment.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For a BLEVE to occur, the boiling liquid must be sufficiently superheated upon loss of containment.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For example, at a pressure of approximately 1 MPa (150 psi), water boils at 177 °C (351 °F).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Superheated water released from a closed container at these conditions will not generate a BLEVE, as homogeneous nucleation of vapor bubbles is not possible.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] There is no consensus about the minimal temperature above which a BLEVE will occur.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] where *T*C is the critical temperature of the fluid (expressed in kelvin).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] According to Reid, BLEVE will occur, more in general, if the expansion crosses a "superheat-limit locus".
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In Reid's model, this curve is essentially the fluid's spinodal curve as represented in a pressure–temperature diagram, and the BLEVE onset is a manifestation of explosive boiling, where the spinodal is crossed "from above", i.e., via sudden depressurization.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, direct correspondence between the superheat limit and the spinodal has not been proven experimentally.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In practical BLEVEs, the way the pressure vessel fails may influence decisively the way the expansion takes place, for example causing pressure waves and non-uniformities.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Additionally, there may be stratification in the liquid, due to local temperature variations.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Because of this, it is possible for BLEVEs to occur at temperatures less than those predicted with Reid's formula.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The term BLEVE is often associated to explosive fires from pressure vessels containing a flammable liquid.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, a BLEVE can occur even with a non-flammable substance such as water, liquid nitrogen, liquid helium or other refrigerants or cryogenics.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Such materials can go through purely physical BLEVEs, not entailing flames or other chemical reactions.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In the case of unignited BLEVEs of liquefied gases, rapid cooling due to the absorption of the enthalpy of vaporization is a hazard that can cause frostbite.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Asphyxiation from the expanding vapors is also possible, if the vapor cloud is not rapidly dispersed, as can be the case inside a building, or in a trough in the case of heavier-than-air gasses.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The vapors can also be toxic, in which case harm and possibly death can occur at relatively low concentrations and, therefore, even far from the source.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If a flammable substance, however, is subject to a BLEVE, it can ignite upon release, either due to friction, mechanical spark or other point sources, or from a pre-existing fire that had engulfed the pressure vessel and caused it to fail in the first place.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In such a case, the burning vapors will further expand, adding to the force of the explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Furthermore, a very significant amount of the escaped fluid will burn in a matter of seconds in a raising fireball, which will generate extremely high levels of thermal radiation.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] While the blast effects can be devastating, a flammable substance BLEVE typically causes more damage due to the fireball thermal radiation than the blast overpressure.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] BLEVEs are often caused by an external fire near the storage vessel causing heating of the contents and pressure build-up.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] While tanks are often designed to withstand great pressure, constant heating can cause the metal to weaken and eventually fail.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the tank is being heated in an area where there is no liquid (such as near its top), it may rupture faster because the boiling liquid does not afford cooling in that area.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Pressure vessels are usually equipped with relief valves that vent off excess pressure, but the tank can still fail if the pressure is not released quickly enough.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A pressure vessel is designed to withstand the set pressure of its relief valves, but only if its mechanical integrity is not weakened as it can be in the case of an impinging fire.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In an impinging fire scenario, flammable vapors released in the BLEVE will ignite upon release, forming a fireball.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The origin of the impinging fire may be from a release of flammable fluid from the vessel itself, or from an external source, including releases from nearby tanks and equipment.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For example, rail tank cars have BLEVEd under the effect of a jet fire from the open relief valve of another derailed tank car.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The main damaging effects of a BLEVE are three: the blast wave from the explosion; the projection of fragments, or missiles, from the pressure vessel; and the thermal radiation from the fireball, where one occurs.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Horizontal cylindrical ("bullet") tanks tend to rupture longitudinally.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] This causes the failed tank and its fragments to get propelled like rockets and travel long distances.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] At Feyzin, three of the propelled fragments weighed in excess of 100 tons and were thrown 150–350 meters (490–1,150 ft) from the source of the explosion.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] One bullet tank at San Juanico travelled 1,200 meters (0.75 mi) in the air before landing, possibly the farthest ever for a BLEVE missile.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Fragments can impact on other tanks or equipment, which may result in a domino effect propagation of the accidental sequence.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Fireballs can rise to significant heights above ground.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] They are spheroidal when developed and rise from the ground in a mushroom shape.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The diameter of fireballs at San Juanico was estimated at 200–300 meters (660–980 ft), with a duration of around 20 seconds.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Such massive fires can injure people at distances of hundreds of meters (e.g., 300 metres (980 feet) at Feyzin and 400 metres (1,300 feet) at San Juanico).
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] An additional hazard from BLEVE-fireball events is the formation of secondary fires, by direct exposure to the fireball thermal radiation, as pool fires from fuel that does not get combusted in the fireball, or from the scattering of blazing tank fragments.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Another secondary effect of importance is the dispersion of a toxic gas cloud, if the vapors involved are toxic and do not catch fire upon release.
[src:boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Chlorine, ammonia and phosgene are example of toxic gases that underwent BLEVE in past accidents and produced toxic clouds as a consequence.
